data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

The **sync-over-async opt-in for the EF Core Cosmos DB provider is removed entirely** in EF Core 11. The Cosmos SDK is async-only, so EF Core previously faked sync support by blocking on async calls internally. That escape hatch is now gone.

**All four methods** in your repository will throw `InvalidOperationException` at runtime:

| Sync (breaks) | Async (replacement) |
|---|---|
| `ToList()` | `ToListAsync()` |
| `First()` | `FirstAsync()` |
| `Count()` | `CountAsync()` |
| `SaveChanges()` | `SaveChangesAsync()` |

### Migrated code

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**
- This is a **runtime** break, not a compile-time one — the sync methods still exist on `IQueryable<T>`, so the compiler won't warn you.
- Callers must be updated to `await` the new return types (`Task<T>`), which typically means `async` propagates up the call stack.
- Remove any `EnableSyncOverAsync()` / `CosmosOptionsExtension` configuration — it will no longer compile.
